{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510525"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11579"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11579"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.17,0.64,0.15,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44047"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4208"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29028"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2100"},{"type":"tags","id":"2599"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5601"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6802"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44047"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman is seen in pre-admission clinic for an elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy in two weeks time. On examination, when the patient is asked to open their mouth as wide as possible and to protrude their tongue (with no phonation and their head neutral) it is noted that only the base of their uvula is visible.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the Mallampati airway score for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1","2","3","4","5"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe modified Mallampati score is a clinical sign used to predict the difficulty of direct laryngoscopy as part of intubation for anaesthesia. It utilises the visualisation of pharyngeal structures as a predictor and ranges from class 1 to 4. It relates the size of the tongue and the amount of mouth opening;\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass 1: \u003C/strong\u003ESoft palate, uvula and pillars are visible\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass 2: \u003C/strong\u003ESoft palate and uvula are visible\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass 3: \u003C/strong\u003EOnly the soft palate and base of the uvula are visible\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClass 4: \u003C/strong\u003EOnly the hard palate is visible\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMallampati et al. (1985) hypothesised and proved that if the base of the tongue is disproportionately large relative to the oropharynx capacity, the angle to the trachea would be acute and the larynx obscured.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe modified Mallampati score as a test on its own is insufficient for accurate prediction of difficult intubation, but may have clinical utility in combination with other difficult airway predictors (ie. obesity, obstructive sleep apnoea etc).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The Mallampati grading score is one component of pre-operative airway assessment for anaesthesia and may be a predictor of direct laryngoscopy difficulty."],"references":["Mallampati SR, Gatt SP, Gugino LD, Desai SP, Waraksa B, Freiberger D, Liu PL. A clinical sign to predict difficult tracheal intubation: a prospective study. Can Anaesth Soc J. 1985;32(4):429-34. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/4027773/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29028"}},"ques